"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885033","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-19","<p>The Department is keeping Virgin’s eligibility for current and future bids under close scrutiny and constant review.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-04-19T16:15:27.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885033/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885033/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-04-16","Virgin Trains","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has plans to withdraw the pre-qualification questionnaire passport from Virgin Trains.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","136021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885034","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-19","<p>The Department is currently updating its Franchise Agreement to reflect the forthcoming General Data Protection Regulations. This will ensure that all Train Operating Companies meet their legal obligations under the new consumer data regime.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-04-19T16:19:58.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885034/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885034/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-04-16","Train Operating Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that train operating companies comply with consumer data legislation.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","136022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885035","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-19","<p>Schedule 8 of the Track Access Agreement between Network Rail and train operating companies (TOCs) sets out the process for compensating TOCs for the impact of unplanned service disruption where they are not at fault. The process is calibrated to compensate TOCs for their revenue lost and their additional costs incurred resulting from unplanned service disruption. Unplanned disruption often leads to TOCs having to incur many additional costs, including the cost of compensation to passengers, replacement bus/taxi costs, staff overtime and administration costs. It also often leads to TOCs receiving lower revenue due to passenger refunds and fewer passengers choosing to travel on the day of disruption and also in future. As such, payments under Schedule 8 are designed to prevent the TOCs making losses as a result of their extra costs and reduction in revenue, leaving the TOC financially neutral as a result of the disruption.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-04-19T16:30:40.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885035/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885035/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-04-16","Train Operating Companies: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the proportion of the profit accrued by train operating companies from schedule 8 payments; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","136023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885036","Cabinet Office","false","2018-04-20","<p>There were no set up or running costs for the Government's twitter account, @youdecide2014, Facebook page @youdecide2014, and Buzzfeed user YouDecide2014.</p><p>The website; www.youdecide2014.uk, was built in-house for free and set up costs (domains, security testing, load testing, hosting, security certificates) were approximately £3500.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2018-04-20T13:30:38.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885036/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885036/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-04-16","Sovereignty: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the (a) set-up and (b) running costs were for the Government's (i) twitter account @youdecide2014, (ii) website www.youdecide2014.uk, (iii) facebook page @youdecide2014 and (iv) Buzzfeed user YouDecide2014.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","136024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885037","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-04-19","<p>Changes to Ministry of Defence (MOD) Accommodation Policy are agreed by the Department, and officials have engaged with CarillionAmey regarding the recent changes to the Service Family Accommodation complaints procedure (JSP 464 Section IX). The management of Stage 1 Complaints is discussed regularly between the Department and CarillionAmey as part of the normal National Housing Prime governance arrangements.</p><p>The MOD is committed to providing Service personnel with accommodation that is at, or exceeds the Decent Homes Standard.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-04-19T16:47:05.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885037/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885037/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-04-16","Armed Forces: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to Joint Service Publication 464 Section IX,  what discussions he has had with CarillionAmey on service family accommodation complaints procedure.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","136025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885038","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-04-19","<p>Ministers meet regularly with the relevant football authorities and representatives of supporters’ groups to discuss a wide range of issues including the Government’s all-seater policy.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-04-19T14:54:28.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885038/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885038/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-04-16","Football: Sportsgrounds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent meetings her Department has had with (a) football fan groups, (b) representatives of Premier League football clubs, (c) representatives of English Football League clubs, (d) the Football Association, Scottish Football Association and Football Association of Wales and (e) Celtic Football Club on safe standing in football grounds.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","136026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885039","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-04-19","<p>I responded to the hon. Member on 16 April 2018.</p><p>I apologise for the delay in responding to the hon. Member; this was due to an administrative error.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-04-19T15:50:04.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885039/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885039/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-04-16","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, by what date he plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Rochdale dated 26 February 2018 on songbirds in Cyprus, reference number IW/0029.","false","Biography information for Tony Lloyd","Rochdale","Tony Lloyd","136027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885040","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-19","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Entitlement to free National Health Service care is based on a person being ordinarily resident in the United Kingdom, not citizenship, nationality or the payment of UK taxes or national insurance contributions.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-04-19T14:44:24.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885040/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885040/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-16","Health Services: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many people were billed by the NHS each year on the grounds of non-UK citizenship in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","136028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885041","Home Office","false","2018-05-08","<p>The Compliant Environment is not a new concept; successive Governments have brought forward policies to protect the UK taxpayer from the misuse of public services and benefits and to tackle illegal migration.</p><p>Compliant Environment measures were never intended to impact on people with lawful immigration status in the UK, such as the Windrush generation.</p><p>We are fully committed to helping those affected to evidence their status in the UK and are making that process as straightforward as possible. A taskforce and helpline has been set up in the Home Office to help those concerned to prove their residence. The taskforce is taking a proactive approach so individuals can easily establish their rights.</p><p>We have also put in place additional protection for landlords, employers and others conducting checks in order to ensure we are not denying work, housing, benefits and services to Commonwealth migrants who have been long-term residents of the UK.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-05-08T14:37:26.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885041/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885041/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-16","Immigrants: Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government made prior to the introduction of the hostile environment immigration policy of that policy's potential effect on Commonwealth migrants who have been long-term residents of the UK.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","136029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885042","Wales Office","false","2018-04-19","<p>The Wales Office, along with other Government departments, continues to work with port operators, key stakeholders, and the Welsh Government, to ensure that traffic continues to flow freely at ports and airports in Wales once the UK has left the EU.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2018-04-19T10:17:14.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885042/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885042/answer",,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2018-04-16","Ports: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, pursuant to the Answer of 29 March 2018 to Question 135100 on Ports: Wales, whether the (a) Government (b) Welsh Government and (c) Port Authorities will provide funding for the additional infrastructure required at Welsh ports as a result of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","136030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885043","Home Office","false","2018-04-18","<p>The handling of 999 calls is an operational matter for the police. It is for elected Police and Crime Commissioners and Chief Constables to decide how their force’s resources are deployed and how best to manage their communications with the public.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In March 2018, as part of its annual effectiveness reports on all police forces in England and Wales, HMICFRS briefly assesses the police’s response to calls.</p><p>The report for Lincolnshire can be found at: <a href="https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmicfrs/wp-content/uploads/peel-police-effectiveness-2017-lincolnshire.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmicfrs/wp-content/uploads/peel-police-effectiveness-2017-lincolnshire.pdf</a>. (page 6)</p><p>The national overview can be found at: <a href="https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmicfrs/wp-content/uploads/peel-police-effectiveness-2017-1.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmicfrs/wp-content/uploads/peel-police-effectiveness-2017-1.pdf</a> (pages 13-14, 48-49)</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-04-18T16:02:47.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885043/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885043/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-16","Emergency Calls: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the adequacy of response times to 999 calls in (a) Lincoln, (b) Lincolnshire and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","136031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885044","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-19","<p>The pay of public health nurses, who have a contract of employment with a local authority, is determined by the local authority. It is for local authorities to determine the terms and conditions, including pay that will best enable them to recruit, retain and motivate the staff they need.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor was explicit that additional funding, above that already factored into the 2015 Spending Round, was tied to major structural reforms to Agenda for Change to help improve recruitment, retention, increase capacity and improve productivity.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","136034 ; 136035","2018-04-19T14:48:38.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885044/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885044/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-16","Nurses: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether the pay offer to NHS nurses includes public health nurses employed by local authorities.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","136032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885045","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-24","<p>On 1 April the Government launched a UK Research and Innovation, a new body that brings together nine councils including the Medical Research Council (MRC), Innovate UK and Research England into a single organisation. UK Research and Innovation aims to ensure the UK maintains its world-leading position in research and innovation.</p><p> </p><p>UK Research and Innovation is one of the main means by which the Government funds medical research. It is committed to transparency in the medical research it funds. Information on all research projects funded by MRC, including information on outcomes and research publications will continue to be published on the Gateway to Research. By publishing this information, the research councils help to improve the public view of the progress of research, down to the individual project level. The Research Councils UK Open Access policy aims to ensure that ideas and knowledge derived from publicly funded research are made available and accessible for public use.</p><p> </p><p>The National Audit Office published a report on cross-government funding of research and development in November 2017. This found that, for research in human health, coordination mechanisms and leadership arrangements are well established and functioning, consolidated data on funding and capability is used to support decision-making, and steps are being taken towards consolidated evaluation of research outcomes</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-04-24T15:04:10.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885045/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885045/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-04-16","Medicine: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the transparency of publicly-funded medical research and development.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","136033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885046","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-19","<p>The pay of public health nurses, who have a contract of employment with a local authority, is determined by the local authority. It is for local authorities to determine the terms and conditions, including pay that will best enable them to recruit, retain and motivate the staff they need.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor was explicit that additional funding, above that already factored into the 2015 Spending Round, was tied to major structural reforms to Agenda for Change to help improve recruitment, retention, increase capacity and improve productivity.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","136032 ; 136035","2018-04-19T14:48:38.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885046/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885046/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-16","Nurses: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure that the (a) pay and (b) terms and conditions of public health nurses employed by local authorities will remain comparable to nurses working directly for the NHS.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","136034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885047","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-19","<p>The pay of public health nurses, who have a contract of employment with a local authority, is determined by the local authority. It is for local authorities to determine the terms and conditions, including pay that will best enable them to recruit, retain and motivate the staff they need.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor was explicit that additional funding, above that already factored into the 2015 Spending Round, was tied to major structural reforms to Agenda for Change to help improve recruitment, retention, increase capacity and improve productivity.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","136032 ; 136034","2018-04-19T14:48:38.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885047/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885047/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-16","Nurses: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether public health nurses employed directly by local authorities will be included in the local government pay award; and whether those nurses will receive pay rises comparable to nurses in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","136035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885048","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-24","<p>The National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) provides support for the development of new drugs, medical devices, diagnostics and treatments, primarily through its investment in research infrastructure in the National Health Service and through a range of research funding programmes. NIHR-supported research supports the early translational and clinical development of new medicines and generates high quality evidence which is made available to inform decisions about the NHS and patients on the effectiveness and cost-effectiveness of medicines, including through National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guidance. There is no explicit link between the terms of NIHR research grants and the price the NHS pays for medicines.</p><p> </p><p>NICE technology appraisal guidance, and the associated funding requirement, play an important role in ensuring that patients have access to cost-effective new medicines, including medicines developed from public research. NICE assesses important new medicines through a robust evaluation process.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS is required by law to ensure that all medicines recommended by NICE are generally funded within three months, ensuring patient access to cost-effective medicines in England. New medicines are not subject to payments under the voluntary Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme, and NHS England monitors access to innovative medicines via the Innovation Scorecard in recognition of the value this Government places on innovation.</p><p> </p><p>The Accelerated Access Review made recommendations to get transformative drugs and treatments to patients faster, while ensuring that the NHS gets value for money and remains at the forefront of innovation. The Department’s response sets out how it will work with industry and healthcare organisations to create an approvals system to ensure this happens. A total of £86 million of funding has already been committed to make the vision a reality.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-04-24T11:11:24.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885048/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885048/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-16","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that medicines developed from public research are (a) accessible and (b) affordable.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","136036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885049","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>I am aware of concerns related to the electoral boundary changes introduced by the Election Commission. We will be monitoring their impact, and have discussed the importance of free and fair elections with the Malaysian Government at the highest levels. Most recently the Minister for Asia and the Pacific raised these issues with the Malaysian Senate President on 18 April.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2018-04-24T16:16:51.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885049/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885049/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-16","Malaysia: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential implications for free and fair elections in Malaysia of the re-drawing of parliamentary constituency boundaries in that country.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","136037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885050","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-19","<p>This function was introduced to allow for simple errors (such as spelling mistakes or messages entered before fully completed) to be rectified.</p><p> </p><p>Jobcentre staff can only remove entries they have made and are not able to remove any other entries, such as those entered by another member of staff or claimant. It is important to note that this facility only removes the entry from the journal, with a permanent record being retained and stored on the system which can be retrieved if requested.</p><p> </p><p>In situations where a Decision Maker’s decision has been revised, an official letter is uploaded to the claimant’s journal detailing the new decision and when it will take effect.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-04-19T16:40:36.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885050/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885050/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-04-16","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will (a) prohibit the removal by departmental officials of documents from a person's universal credit journal and (b) ensure that in cases of official error the journal record is amended through the addition of a revising letter.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","136038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885051","Treasury","false","2018-04-24","<p>Guidance on the VAT treatment of loans and other credit is set out in “VAT Notice 701/49: finance”, available on the gov.uk website. As provided for in the VAT Act 1994, the guidance sets out that loans and grants of credits are exempt from VAT.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-04-24T16:30:01.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885051/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885051/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-16","Loans: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the clarity of Government guidance for private companies on the charging of VAT on loans.","false","Biography information for Karen Lee","Lincoln","Karen Lee","136039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885052","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>I am concerned about the potential implications the new Anti-Fake News Bill could have, including for British citizens, media and business, and that this Bill was passed without meaningful public consultation or debate. The UK has, along with European partners, written to the Malaysian Government setting out our concerns, including around the potential extra territorial effects of the Bill, and requesting a meeting to discuss this. Most recently, the Minister for Asia and the Pacific discussed this issue with the Malaysian Senate President on 18 April. The UK will continue to promote freedom of expression and the right of the media including foreign media organisations, to report honestly and impartially.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson","136041","2018-04-24T16:25:00.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885052/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885052/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-16","Malaysia: Freedom of Expression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on freedom of speech and expression in Malaysia of the Anti-Fake News Bill recently passed by the Malaysian Parliament.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","136040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885053","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-24","<p>I am concerned about the potential implications the new Anti-Fake News Bill could have, including for British citizens, media and business, and that this Bill was passed without meaningful public consultation or debate. The UK has, along with European partners, written to the Malaysian Government setting out our concerns, including around the potential extra territorial effects of the Bill, and requesting a meeting to discuss this. Most recently, the Minister for Asia and the Pacific discussed this issue with the Malaysian Senate President on 18 April. The UK will continue to promote freedom of expression and the right of the media including foreign media organisations, to report honestly and impartially.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson","136040","2018-04-24T16:25:00.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885053/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885053/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-16","Malaysia: Freedom of Expression","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential implications of provisions in the Anti-Fake News Bill recently passed by the Malaysian Parliament, which apply to reporting by foreign media organisations, for the ability of the BBC World Service to operate freely in that country.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","136041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885054","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-24","<p>NHS England has advised that they have, over the last three years, received fewer than 10 Individual Funding Requests applications and therefore there have been fewer than 10 approvals relating to the use of Kuvan.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Health and Social Care has not had further recent discussions with the manufacturer (BioMarin) since the oral contribution of my Rt. hon. Friend the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Mental Health and Inequalities (Jackie Doyle-Price).</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","136098","2018-04-24T15:36:59.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885054/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885054/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-16","Sapropterin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many individual patient funding requests have been approved for the use of Kuvan.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","136042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885055","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-24","<p>Health Education England (HEE) supports the National Health Service by ensuring that the workforce has the right number, skills, values and behaviours, at the right time and the right place.</p><p> </p><p>HEE’s commissions for 2017/18 are included in their third national workforce plan for England, through which they are investing in the appropriate areas, which can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://hee.nhs.uk/our-work/workforce-strategy" target="_blank">https://hee.nhs.uk/our-work/workforce-strategy</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-04-24T11:15:55.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885055/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885055/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-16","Urinary Tract Infections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will ensure that funding is provided for the training and recruitment of chronic urinary tract infection specialists in the NHS.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","136043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885056","Treasury","false","2018-04-24","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are independent from Government. The question has been passed on to the FCA.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-04-24T13:57:06.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885056/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885056/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-16","1MDB: Malaysia","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the progress of investigations by UK authorities into financial crimes related to the 1MDB fund in Malaysia; what requests for information have been made to the Malaysian authorities during the course of those investigations; and what responses have been received to such requests.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","136044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885057","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-24","<p>A search of the Department’s Ministerial correspondence database has identified 56 items of correspondence received since 1 April 2017 about the Lower Urinary Tract Services Clinic in north London. This figure represents correspondence received by the Department’s Ministerial correspondence unit only.</p><p> </p><p>The Trust has been working to address the recommendations of the Royal College of Physicians following a service review of the Lower Urinary Tract Service, before the clinic is re-opened to new patients. The Trust is currently in negotiations with commissioners to establish the re-opening of the clinic in the 2018/19 contract.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-24T15:39:50.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885057/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885057/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-16","Whittington Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what representations he has received on the reopening to new patients of the Lower Urinary Tract Services Clinic in north London.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","136045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885058","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-24","<p>This information is not collected.</p><p> </p><p>Clinical commissioning groups provide an estimate of their overall expenditure on problems of the genitourinary system in their annual Programme Budgeting data submission to NHS England. The aggregate value of these estimates was £3,146 million in financial year 2016/17.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-24T15:38:00.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885058/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885058/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-16","Urinary Tract Infections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent estimate he has made of the annual cost to the NHS of treating chronic urinary tract infections.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","136046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885059","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-20","<p>I have not held any discussions with my Indian counterpart on this issue.</p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2018-04-20T13:04:16.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885059/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885059/answer","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885059/answer/previousversion/52868","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885059/answer/previousversion/52868",,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-16","India: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Indian counterpart on recent protests against the ruling of that country’s Supreme Court on the Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes Act of 1989 dated 20 March 2018; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","136047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885060","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-20","<p>India’s Government has filed a petition to review the 20 March Supreme Court ruling. This is currently being considered. I believe it is right to let India’s executive and judiciary settle this issue within the country’s constitutional and judicial framework.</p><p>In order to support Dalit women who are victims of violence in gaining access to justice, the British Government runs programmes with local partners, including training and engaging state Criminal Justice officials across five States.</p><p> </p>","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson",,"2018-04-20T13:06:31.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885060/answer","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885060/answer","Uxbridge and South Ruislip","Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885060/answer/previousversion/52870","Biography information for Boris Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885060/answer/previousversion/52870",,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-16","India: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the Indian Supreme Court’s ruling of 20 March 2018 on the Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes Act of 1989 on (a) levels of caste-based discrimination and violence in India and (b) the ability of any victims of such discriminatory or violent acts to seek legal redress in that country’s courts.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","136048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885061","Department for International Trade","false","2018-04-24","<p>India is a priority market for DIT's Food and Drink sector team which works closely with DEFRA, UK regional colleagues (including Devolved Administrations), dedicated overseas staff in India, UK Export Finance and trade policy officials. This collaborative export promotion work helps UK companies enter and grow sustainably in the market. In addition, India and the UK have identified food and drink as a specific workstream in the Joint Trade Review.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-04-24T16:52:02.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885061/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885061/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-04-16","Food: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what progress he plans to make on increasing food and drink exports to India in advance of the next India-UK Joint Economic and Trade Committee.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","136049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885062","Department for International Trade","false","2018-04-24","<p>The UK-India Joint Trade Review successfully reported back to the Joint Economic and Trade Committee (JETCO) in January. Ministers endorsed several recommendations from the Review, including further collaboration between our Governments to explore addressing non-tariff barriers to trade specifically in the food and drink sector. Detailed inputs from industry will be crucial to informing this work so we welcome continued engagement with business. As my officials finalise workplans with their Indian counterparts they will be communicating to business how they might provide input.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-04-24T16:47:55.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885062/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885062/answer",,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-04-16","Food: India","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of establishing a business-led Joint Working Group on Food and Drink as part of the India-UK Joint Trade Review.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","136050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885063","Department for Education","false","2018-04-19","<p>My right hon. Friend, the Secretary of State is planning to appoint a suitable independent person to report on the operation of the Teaching Excellence and Student Outcomes Framework by autumn 2018. The department is currently engaged in a process for identifying people who have both the required experience and can command the confidence of the sector.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-04-19T16:04:37.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885063/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885063/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-16","Teachers: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when he plans to appoint the independent chair of the review into the Teaching Excellence Framework.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","136051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885064","Department for Education","false","2018-05-01","<p>The Panel of Apprentices, announced in April 2017, is particularly important to help the Institute for Apprenticeships improve the quality of apprenticeships as it reflects the importance of apprentices’ experiences across a broad range of different occupational routes.</p><p> </p><p>I attended by telephone the meeting of the Board of the Institute for Apprenticeships in December last year. I am hoping to meet with the Panel of Apprentices in the near future.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-05-01T16:56:43.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885064/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885064/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885064/answer/previousversion/52869","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885064/answer/previousversion/52869",,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-16","Institute for Apprenticeships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the Minister of State for Apprenticeships and Skills has held meetings with the panel of apprentices that reports to the Board of the Institute for Apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","136052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885065","Department for Education","false","2018-04-19","<p>This is a matter for the Institute for Apprenticeships. I have asked its Chief Executive, Sir Gerry Berragan, to write to the hon. Member and a copy of his reply will be placed in the Libraries of both Houses.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-04-19T16:40:08.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885065/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885065/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-16","Institute for Apprenticeships: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many applications his Department received for the Panel of Apprentices in 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","136053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885066","Department for Education","false","2018-04-19","<p>There have been no decisions taken on the UK’s participation in the European Apprenticeship Network because the future scope of the programme has yet to be agreed. Our participation will be a matter for negotiations about our future relationship with the EU.</p><p>We will seek to continue to take part in specific policies and programmes which are in the UK and the EU’s joint interest, such as those that promote science, education and culture.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-04-19T16:43:54.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885066/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885066/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-16","Apprentices: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what plans he has to allocated funding for the UK's participation in the European Apprentice Network after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","136054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885067","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-19","<p>There are a number of train operating companies that operate on the West Coast mainline and their train maintenance is an individual commercial decision for each of these operators.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-04-19T16:12:35.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885067/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885067/answer",,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-04-16","West Coast Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which companies are responsible for train maintenance on the West Coast Main Line; and by whom those companies are owned.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","136055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885068","Home Office","false","2018-04-30","<p>The Home Office publishes Open Data Tables on the number of selected offences involving a knife or a sharp instrument recorded by the police in England and Wales at the police force area level. The data are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-recorded-crime-open-data-tables</a></p><p> </p><p>The police have the resources they need to do their important work. The police funding settlement for 2018/19 increases overall investment in policing by £460m, including over £280m from increased local funding through Council Tax. Decisions about the allocation of police resources and deployment of officers are for Chief Constables and democratically accountable PCCs. They are responsible for ensuring the needs of the local community are met. Many PCCs have set out their intention to use their additional funding to maintain or enhance front line policing.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-04-30T14:10:44.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885068/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885068/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-16","Knives: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to her article in The Daily Telegraph of 7 April 2018, we are determined to tackle violent crime, and there are enough officers on the streets to do so, if she will publish the statistical data on which the levels of knife crime were cited.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","136056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885069","Department for Education","false","2018-04-19","<p>The department has worked with all the schools and the new trusts to provide appropriate support and resources, including funding, so that each of the schools has what they require to improve pupil outcomes and secure the financial future for those schools.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-04-19T16:26:01.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885069/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885069/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-16","Wakefield City Academies Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what additional funding his Department has provided to trusts that are taking over schools from the Wakefield City Academy Trust.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","136057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885070","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-19","<p>Lyme disease is a bacterial infection and most people recover completely with prompt antibiotic treatment that reduces the risk of further symptoms developing and increases the chance of complete recovery. NHS England specialised services are not the responsible commissioner for treatment of Lyme disease: Lyme disease is diagnosed and treated in primary care or in clinical commissioning groups’ infectious diseases hospital services according to the Prescribed Services Manual.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has funded four independent systematic reviews, published at the end of 2017, to further strengthen the evidence base for epidemiology, diagnosis, treatment and prevention of Lyme disease. The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence has recently published its clinical guideline on Lyme disease, which provides the latest information for clinicians in diagnosing and managing Lyme disease. The guideline aims to raise awareness of when Lyme disease should be considered and to ensure that people have prompt and consistent diagnosis and treatment.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-19T16:51:22.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885070/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885070/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-16","Lyme Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to encourage NHS England to develop specialist services for Lyme disease patients.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","136058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885071","Cabinet Office","false","2018-06-06","<p>As at 19th March 2018, the Cabinet Office employed 59 apprentices who were actively completing an apprenticeship, this equated to 1.13% of our workforce.</p><p> </p><p>This is broken down in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Cabinet Office HR</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Civil Service Group</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Civil Service HR</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Civil Service Learning</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Civil Service Resourcing</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Commonwealth Summit Unit</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Constitution Group</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Corporate Finance</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Economic &amp; Domestic Affairs Secretariat</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Government Communications Service</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Government Digital Service</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Government in Parliament</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Government Property Unit</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Govt Commercial Organisation</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Head of the Office of the Registrar of Consultant Lobbyists</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Infrastructure &amp; Projects Authority</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Knowledge &amp; Information Mgmt Team</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National Security Secretariat</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Office of the Parliamentary Counsel</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Prime Minister's Office</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Private Office Group</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-06-06T14:22:45.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885071/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/885071/answer"