"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882168","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-04-18","<p>There are currently no plans to publish the monthly scorecards relating to the prison facilities management contracts with Amey.</p><p> </p><p>The MoJ closely monitors private providers performance and will not hesitate to act where standards fall short.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-04-18T15:47:17.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882168/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882168/answer",,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-04-13","Amey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 19 March 2018 to Question 132514, if he will publish the monthly scorecards for each prison in which Amey is responsible for maintenance since such scorecards were first recorded.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","135282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882169","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-20","<p>Hedgehogs are listed under Schedule 6 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 so are protected from being killed using prohibited methods such as crossbows, traps and snares. We are committed, through the Government’s 25 Year Environment Plan, to creating or restoring 500,000 hectares of wildlife rich habitat for the benefit of species such as the hedgehog.</p><p> </p><p>To designate hedgehogs as a protected species would require them to be listed under Schedule 5 of the Act. There are no plans to do so as protection of the hedgehogs’ habitat from destruction or disturbance, as defined in the Act, could mean that aspects of garden and land maintenance, or use, would constitute a criminal offence and this may have the unintended consequence of discouraging the creation of hedgehog habitat.</p><p> </p><p>The National Planning Policy Framework sets out the Government’s policy on planning, and states that the planning system should contribute to and enhance the natural and local environment by minimising impacts on biodiversity, including by establishing coherent ecological networks. The accompanying planning practice guidance (<a href="http://www.gov.uk/guidance/natural-environment" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/guidance/natural-environment</a>) provides further advice on how this should be achieved by local planning authorities. The Government is currently consulting on amendments to the National Planning Policy Framework.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-04-20T10:05:36.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882169/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882169/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-13","Hedgehogs: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans his Department has to (a) designate hedgehogs as a protected species and (b) ensure that planning guidance takes into account the need to preserve hedgehog habitats.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","135283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882170","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-04-23","<p>Door to door clothing collections raise millions of pounds each year for charities and also prevent hundreds of thousands of tonnes of textiles going to landfill. Where there are problems with bogus or unlicensed charitable collections then this is for local licensing authorities and the police to enforce.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-04-23T16:11:45.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882170/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882170/answer",,,,,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-04-13","Charitable Donations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to reduce the level of unlicensed charity bag collections.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","135284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882171","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-23","<p>No such meetings have taken place.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-23T15:47:14.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882171/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882171/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","Leukaemia: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what meetings he has had with representatives of blood cancer patients to discuss the availability of treatment options on the NHS for patients diagnosed with relapsed acute lymphoblastic leukaemia.","false","Biography information for Mark Tami","Alyn and Deeside","Mark Tami","135285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882172","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-23","<p>No such assessment has been made.</p><p> </p><p>There is a well-established framework for enabling access to cost effective new cancer medicines in England. All new licensed cancer medicines are referred to the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) for inclusion within the Technology Appraisal Programme, this referral is irrespective of the clinical indication concerned. Where cancer medicines are approved by NICE for use in England, NHS England makes these available immediately. NICE now also has the ability to refer licensed medicines demonstrating promising, but not yet certain, benefits for inclusion within the Cancer Drugs Fund.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-23T15:46:26.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882172/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882172/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","Leukaemia: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what comparative assessment he has made of the adequacy of the availability of treatment options for patients with relapsed acute lymphoblastic leukaemia in the (a) UK and (b) EU countries.","false","Biography information for Mark Tami","Alyn and Deeside","Mark Tami","135286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882173","Home Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>The Modern Slavery Helpline is run by the charity, Unseen and is completely independent of Government. Information about the number and types of calls received by the Modern Slavery Helpline can be found on the Unseen website <a href="http://www.modernslaveryhelpline.org/information/stats" target="_blank">www.modernslaveryhelpline.org/information/stats</a> or by contacting Unseen directly on <a href="https://www.unseenuk.org/contact-us" target="_blank">https://www.unseenuk.org/contact-us</a></p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-04-23T16:40:06.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882173/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882173/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-13","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has conducted an assessment of the (a) performance and (b) effectiveness of the national modern slavery helpline.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","135287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882174","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-23","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is the independent body responsible for developing authoritative, evidence-based guidance for the National Health Service on whether drugs and other treatments represent an effective use of NHS resources.</p><p> </p><p>NICE’s methods and processes for the assessment of drugs have been carefully developed over time and are internationally respected. NICE continues to keep its procedures under periodic review to ensure that they remain effective and fit for purpose.</p><p> </p><p>In developing guidance on drugs and other treatments through its technology appraisal programme, NICE routinely takes into account all health-related costs and benefits relating to the treatment. NICE may also take into account wider costs and benefits where relevant in making its recommendations.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-23T15:45:31.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882174/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882174/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","Rare Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of (a) the accuracy of NICE's calculation of the wider value of (i) rare disease and (ii) rarer cancer treatments and (b) the extent to which NICE accounts in that calculation for (A) additional medical benefits, (B) wider economic consequences and (C) social impact costs.","false","Biography information for Mark Tami","Alyn and Deeside","Mark Tami","135288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882175","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-23","<p>NHS England is responsible for the delivery of vaccinations to those undergoing stem cell transplants (under the pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccination immunosuppressed indications) as part of the Public Health functions agreement section 7a. The funding is via the directly enhanced services, whereby the first dose delivered has an automatic payment. Where a patient requires additional pneumococcal vaccination (if severely immunosuppressed) the specialist clinicians are expected to use their discretion and deliver this or advise the general practitioner to deliver. The practice is required to make arrangements with their local commissioners with regards to payment.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-23T16:11:31.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882175/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882175/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","Pneumococcal Diseases: Vaccination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 21 December 2017 to Question 119731 on Pneumoccocol Diseases: Vaccination, whether NHS England is responsible for funding the vaccination of adults who have undergone stem cell transplantation under paragraph 4.2 of the NHS public health functions agreement 2017-18: Service specification no.8 Pneumococcal immunisation programme.","false","Biography information for Mark Tami","Alyn and Deeside","Mark Tami","135289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882176","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-20","<p>Hedgehogs are listed under Schedule 6 of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 so are protected from being killed using prohibited methods such as a crossbows, traps and snares. The Government is committed, through the 25 Year Environment Plan, to creating or restoring 500,000 hectares of wildlife rich habitat for the benefit of species such as the hedgehog.</p><p> </p><p>To designate hedgehogs as a protected species would require them to be listed under Schedule 5 of the Act. There are no plans to do so as protection of the hedgehogs’ habitat from destruction or disturbance, as defined in the Act, could mean that aspects of garden and land maintenance would constitute a criminal offence, and this may have the unintended consequence of discouraging the creation of hedgehog habitat.</p><p> </p><p><em> </em></p><p><em> </em></p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-04-20T16:45:11.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882176/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882176/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-13","Hedgehogs: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 28 March 2018 to Question 134095 on Department for Transport: Hedgehogs, what steps he is taking as species champion for the native hedgehog to make hedgehogs a protected species.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","135290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882177","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-20","<p>The Government has not had any discussions with the charity sector on reducing the use of single use plastic bags in door to door collections.</p><p> </p><p>Following a public consultation last year, the Fundraising Regulator has strengthened its Code of Practice, which requires charitable house to house collectors not to post collection bags to properties that indicate they do not wish to receive them, thus reducing the distribution of unwanted charity collection bags.</p><p>Charity textile collections offer a convenient way for people to reduce their environmental impact and contribute to the 650,000 tonnes of clothing reused or recycled which might otherwise be sent to landfill, while also benefiting charitable causes.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-04-20T10:13:40.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882177/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882177/answer",,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-04-13","Plastic Bags: Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions the Government has had with the charity sector on reducing the use of single-use plastic bags in door-to-door collections.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","135291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882178","Home Office","false","2018-04-19","<p>The Home Office does not hold the information requested. Data on prosecutions are the responsibility of the Ministry of Justice.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-04-19T16:26:22.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882178/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882178/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-13","Drugs: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what data her Department holds on the number of people aged under 18 years of age convicted for drug related offences outside the local authority area where they live.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","135292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882179","Home Office","false","2018-04-18","<p>The National County Lines Co-ordination Centre is being established by the National Police Chiefs’ Council lead and the National Crime Agency. The Centre will be fully operational later this year subject to recruitment of staff.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-04-18T10:54:27.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882179/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882179/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-13","Drugs: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the timetable is for the National County Lines Co-ordination Centre to be fully operational.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","135293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882180","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-23","<p>The information sought by the hon. Member will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-04-23T16:31:11.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882180/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882180/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-04-13","Nuclear Power: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 28 March 2018 to Question 132826 on Nuclear Power: Consultants, if he will set out (a) the title of each report that he plans to publish and the timetable for doing so and (b) the title of each report that he does not plan to publish and in each case the reasons why.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","135294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882181","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-04-19","<p>The UK has carried out a total of 249 airstrikes in Syria between March 2017 – March 2018. These are broken down by month in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Month</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Strikes</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td><td><p>March</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>April</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>May</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>June</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>38</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>August</p></td><td><p>49</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>September</p></td><td><p>32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>November</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>December</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2018</strong></p></td><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>February</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>March</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>249</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The data contained in this answer is believed to be complete and correct at the time of issue. The Ministry of Defence’s operational activity databases are frequently reviewed and any errors and omissions are corrected. It is therefore possible that future answer might not match this answer exactly. Our aim is to ensure that our records are as complete and correct as possible.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-04-19T16:03:52.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882181/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882181/answer","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882181/answer/previousversion/52603","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882181/answer/previousversion/52603",,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-04-13","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many military airstrikes were carried out by the RAF in Syria in ach month between March 2017 and March 2018.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","135295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882182","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-04-18","<p>The Multi-Role Vehicle - Protected (MRV-P) programme is being delivered in two packages. For package 1, the Command, Liaison and Logistics vehicles, the Joint Light Tactical Vehicle manufactured in the United States by Oshkosh has been identified as the preferred option, with the US Department of Defense Foreign Military Sales acceptance letters expected to be signed shortly. Package 2 will provide the Troop Carrying Vehicles and Future Protected Battlefield Ambulance, and is currently the subject of an ongoing competition, with a decision expected in early 2019.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-04-18T15:07:34.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882182/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882182/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-04-13","Army: Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent progress had been made on the Multi Role Vehicle (Protected) Group (a) 1 and (b) 2 contracts.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","135296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882183","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>We are not aware of any such representations.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-04-23T12:43:02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882183/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882183/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-13","Scandinavia: Sami","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has received representations from (a) hon. Members, (b) NGOs or (c) members of the public on the protection of the Sami community in Scandinavia.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","135254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882184","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>The rights of the Sami people are protected under the laws of Norway, Finland and Sweden. I have therefore not discussed this directly with my ministerial counterparts.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-04-23T14:06:23.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882184/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882184/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-04-13","Scandinavia: Sami","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has had any discusisons with his Norwegian, Finnish or Swedish counterparts on the welfare of the Sami people and the protection of their culture.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","135255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882185","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-18","<p>The Department does not hold this information for the entire UK business population.</p><p> </p><p>However, it is available for UK small and medium-sized enterprises (fewer than 250 employees), which account for over 99% of the total UK business population.</p><p>In 2016, the distribution of business premises ownership for UK small and medium-sized enterprises was as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Ownership status of business premises</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Rented from a private or commercial landlord</p></td><td><p>43%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Owned by business</p></td><td><p>40%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Leased</p></td><td><p>12%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>4%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: BEIS 2016 Longitudinal Small Business Survey</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-04-18T13:53:51.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882185/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882185/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-04-13","Business Premises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what information the Government holds on the proportion of UK businesses that (a) own their own premises and (b) rent their premises.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","135256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882186","Treasury","false","2018-04-18","<p>The government has carefully considered the case for removing plant and machinery (P&amp;M). The vast majority of P&amp;M is not rateable.</p><p> </p><p>For P&amp;M that is rateable, delivering a change would be fiscally costly and operationally challenging. P&amp;M such as sprinkler systems, lighting, and heating systems are integral features of property. To exclude them from the calculation of rateable values, one would need to determine the market rent of the building if it did not include these key integral features.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-04-18T13:51:38.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882186/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882186/answer",,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-04-13","Non-domestic Rates: Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of removing from business rates (a) new investment in plant and machinery and (b) all plant and machinery.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","135257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882187","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-23","<p>Reviews of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) awards, which can be paid at one of eight rates, are a key part of the benefit and ensure that claimants continue to receive the correct level of support. Planned interventions take place up to one year before an award is due to expire. PIP was introduced in April 2013, therefore no claimants in receipt of 10 year awards have yet received a planned intervention.</p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-04-23T11:49:42.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882187/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882187/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-04-13","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of people who have ten year personal independence awards have had a planned intervention in advance of the original end date of their claim in each of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","135258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882188","Home Office","false","2018-04-18","<p>A response will be sent to the Hon. Member’s enquiry in line with the published service standard of responding within twenty working days.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-18T16:36:22.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882188/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882188/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-13","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to respond to the letter of 28 March 2018 from the hon. Member for Croydon North a visa enquiry on behalf of a constituent.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","135259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882189","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-20","<p>Reviews of Personal Independence Payment (PIP), which can be paid at one of eight rates, are a key part of the benefit and ensure that claimants continue to receive the correct level of support based on their needs. Planned reviews take place a year before the award is due to expire to ensure that the review is completed before the award goes out of payment. Following a planned review the existing award may be adjusted by the amount received and/or the award duration to reflect the current needs of the claimant. Awards may stay the same, go up, down, or cease altogether depending on the claimant’s assessed level of needs.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-04-20T14:59:19.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882189/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882189/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-04-13","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons personal independence payment claimants who undergo reviews 12 months in advance of their award ending have their payments stopped immediately should they fail those reviews.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","135260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882190","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-25","<p>As a matter of policy, and as set out in the Written Ministerial Statement of 25 January 2018, my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State will seek an independent assessment of a company’s financial resilience before Hydraulic Fracture Consent is granted. If or when an application for Hydraulic Fracture Consent is received from Cuadrilla, the Secretary of State will ask for an assessment of the company’s financial resilience.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-04-25T15:29:36.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882190/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882190/answer",,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-04-13","Cuadrilla Resources: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to his Written Ministerial Statement of 25 January 2018 on energy policy, HCWS428, if he will ask the Infrastructure and Projects Authority to assess the financial resilience of Cuadrilla Resources Ltd, including its ability to fund decommissioning costs, as part of the Government's consideration of that company's application for consent to fracture its first horizontal well at Preston New Road, Lancashire; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","135261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882191","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-18","<p>The Parliamentary and Health Services Ombudsman (PHSO) report ‘Ignoring the alarms: how NHS eating disorder services are failing patients’ published in December 2017 described the service failings that led to the avoidable and tragic death of Averil Hart, a 19 year old who suffered from an eating disorder.</p><p> </p><p>In response to the PHSO report, a working group has been set up, chaired by Professor Tim Kendall (NHS England and NHS Improvement National Clinical Director), to address the recommendations and take them into account for planned improvement to eating disorder services. The second recommendation in the report recommends that Health Education England (HEE) reviews its current education and training to address the gaps in the provision of eating disorder specialists and HEE is now working with cross system partners within the working group to address this recommendation.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-04-18T16:08:51.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882191/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882191/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","Eating Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to increase the number of eating disorder specialists in the area of adult eating disorder treatment and care.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","135262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882192","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-19","<p>Information on the number of patients living with HIV who were offered and received an annual health assessment for cardiovascular disease, renal impairment, diabetes and bone health in each NHS England region is not collected centrally. An ongoing assessment for cardiovascular disease, renal impairment, diabetes and bone health is part of the core clinical and therapeutic management of patients with HIV.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has published a service specification for HIV services which defines the standards of care expected from organisations funded by NHS England to provide specialised care. The service specification refers to the British HIV Association routine investigation and monitoring guidelines, which set the clinical standard for clinical assessments and tests. These guidelines include annual monitoring for co-morbidities and are subject to local and national clinical audit. A copy of the service specification can be viewed on NHS England’s website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/npc-crg/blood-and-infection-group-f/f03/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/commissioning/spec-services/npc-crg/blood-and-infection-group-f/f03/</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-04-19T11:26:29.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882192/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882192/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-04-13","HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the number of patients living with HIV who (a) were offered and (b) received an annual health assessment for cardiovascular disease, renal impairment, diabetes and bone health in each NHS England region in the last year for which figures are available; and what plans he has to ensure that all people living with HIV (i) are offered and (ii) attend an annual health assessment to manage co-morbidities.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","135263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882193","Home Office","false","2018-04-18","<p>Time of birth is currently recorded in cases of multiple live births in England and Wales. There are no current plans to review the detail collected and recorded in other live births.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-04-18T16:39:39.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882193/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882193/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-13","Birth Certificates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of recording the time of birth on birth certificates; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","135264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882194","Home Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>As part of NRM reform, Home Office Ministers committed to testing ‘transition pathways’ with local authorities to identifying best practice in supporting victims to move out of central government-funded support and into local communities.</p><p> </p><p>Nine local authorities applied to be part of this testing process and applications were assessed based on whether their proposals aligned with the aims of the project. For example, whether the proposals related to support for victims at the end of the NRM process, and whether they would provide opportunity to test the role of local authorities and their partners in supporting victims to transition out of NRM care.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-04-23T16:46:00.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882194/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882194/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-13","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many local authorities applied for the modern slavery pilot scheme; and how were successful applicants selected.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","135265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882195","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-23","<p>Over 99% of claims are made online, and claimants can contact their Work Coach at any point during their claim via email and their online journal if they require further help, including accessing the service.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-04-23T14:35:23.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882195/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882195/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-04-13","Universal Credit: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of visits to the Universal Credit website result in claimants successfully accessing the service following the (a) creation and (b) re-use of a verified account.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","135266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882196","Department for Education","false","2018-04-18","<p>The campaign by ITV and INEOS did not require the approval of the Department for Education. It is up to schools to decide what activities to offer to their pupils, and for private companies to decide the contents of the campaigns they run.</p><p> </p><p>The department supports the adoption of programmes that increase physical activity amongst pupils. Regular physical activity has been linked not only to improved physical health but also to improved mental wellbeing and academic attainment. Programmes such as the Daily Mile are simple, inclusive and can successfully engage the least active children in physical activity, helping them to achieve the 60 active minutes each day recommended by the UK chief medical officers.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-04-18T15:37:27.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882196/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882196/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-04-13","Children: Exercise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the campaign being run in schools by ITV and INEOS to promote the Daily Mile required the approval of his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","135267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882197","Home Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I gave to the Hon. Member for Camberwell and Peckham on 11th April 2018, UIN 111921;</p><p> </p><p>So called 'honour-based' violence, including Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) and forced marriage, is a terrible form of abuse, and this Government is clear that we will not allow political or cultural sensitivities to get in the way of tackling it. Work to tackle these crimes is an integral part of our cross-Government Violence Against Women and Girls (VAWG) strategy, published last year.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS FGM Enhanced Dataset provides information on the number of women and girls with FGM who are being cared for by the NHS in England and has been published quarterly and annually by NHS Digital since 2014. A detailed breakdown of these statistics by local authority, age at which FGM was carried out and country where FGM was undertaken is available online at <a href="http://content.digital.nhs.uk/fgm" target="_blank">http://content.digital.nhs.uk/fgm</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The joint Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office and Home Office Forced Marriage Unit (FMU) operates a public helpline to provide advice and support to victims of forced marriage as well as to professionals dealing with cases. Statistics on the number of cases dealt with by the FMU are published annually, including a breakdown by region and age and are available online at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/forced-marriage#statistics-on-forced-marriage-collected-by-fmu" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/forced-marriage#statistics-on-forced-marriage-collected-by-fmu</a>. The statistics are available for the region of London. However, they cannot be broken down into specific London boroughs for data protection reasons. For example, the number of cases from a specific borough may be low enough to allow a victim to be identified, and the FMU must safeguard those it supports.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","135269","2018-04-23T16:49:23.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882197/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882197/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-13","Female Genital Mutilation: Lewisham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of children under the age of 18 who are living in the London Borough of Lewisham and have undergone female genital mutilation (a) in the UK and (b) abroad in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","135268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882198","Home Office","false","2018-04-23","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I gave to the Hon. Member for Camberwell and Peckham on 11th April 2018, UIN 111921;</p><p> </p><p>So called 'honour-based' violence, including Female Genital Mutilation (FGM) and forced marriage, is a terrible form of abuse, and this Government is clear that we will not allow political or cultural sensitivities to get in the way of tackling it. Work to tackle these crimes is an integral part of our cross-Government Violence Against Women and Girls (VAWG) strategy, published last year.</p><p> </p><p>The NHS FGM Enhanced Dataset provides information on the number of women and girls with FGM who are being cared for by the NHS in England and has been published quarterly and annually by NHS Digital since 2014. A detailed breakdown of these statistics by local authority, age at which FGM was carried out and country where FGM was undertaken is available online at <a href="http://content.digital.nhs.uk/fgm" target="_blank">http://content.digital.nhs.uk/fgm</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The joint Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office and Home Office Forced Marriage Unit (FMU) operates a public helpline to provide advice and support to victims of forced marriage as well as to professionals dealing with cases. Statistics on the number of cases dealt with by the FMU are published annually, including a breakdown by region and age and are available online at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/forced-marriage#statistics-on-forced-marriage-collected-by-fmu" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/forced-marriage#statistics-on-forced-marriage-collected-by-fmu</a>. The statistics are available for the region of London. However, they cannot be broken down into specific London boroughs for data protection reasons. For example, the number of cases from a specific borough may be low enough to allow a victim to be identified, and the FMU must safeguard those it supports.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","135268","2018-04-23T16:49:23.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882198/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882198/answer",,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-04-13","Forced Marriage: Lewisham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of children under the age of 18 who are living in the London Borough of Lewisham who have been subjected to a forced marriage in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","135269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882199","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-04-19","<p>National statistics on average net weekly household income are set out in the annual &quot;Households Below Average Income&quot; publication. Average incomes are not available at constituency level in this publication because the survey sample sizes are too small to support the production of robust estimates at this geography. However figures at a regional level are available as a three year rolling average. National figures are available for individual years.</p><p> </p><p>Figures on average incomes for London and for England can be found in the link below, in table 2.5ts, and sets out median and mean incomes before housing costs (BHC) and after housing costs (AHC). Figures for the UK can be found in table 2.1ts, which shows UK income deciles but also the median and mean incomes, both before and after housing costs.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/691966/income-values-and-inequality-measures-hbai-1994-95-2016-17-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/691966/income-values-and-inequality-measures-hbai-1994-95-2016-17-tables.ods</a></p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-04-19T16:34:37.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882199/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/882199/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-04-13","Personal Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average net weekly household income was for people in (a) Lewisham Deptford constituency, (b) London, (c) England, and (d) the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","135270"
